6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both OKX and Phemex calculate funding rates every 8 hours using similar mark price methodologies, but OKX typically shows higher funding rate volatility due to its larger open interest and retail trader base. Phemex's rates tend to be more stable but can spike during low liquidity periods. OKX offers more granular rate history and better API access for tracking rate changes, while Phemex provides clearer rate displays in their simplified interface."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rates for arbitrage?","answer":"OKX typically has more volatile funding rates with broader arbitrage opportunities, while Phemex offers more predictable rates. OKX's higher trading volume creates larger rate swings, especially on major pairs during high volatility periods."},{"question":"How do maker fees impact funding rate profitability?","answer":"Phemex's 0.01% maker fee gives it a significant advantage over OKX's 0.02% for frequent funding rate arbitrage. This 0.01% difference can substantially impact net returns when holding positions across multiple funding periods."},{"question":"Which platform has more reliable funding rate data?","answer":"OKX provides more comprehensive funding rate history and better API documentation for systematic trading. Phemex offers cleaner rate displays but has less historical data depth for backtesting arbitrage strategies."},{"question":"Do both exchanges support cross-margin for funding arbitrage?","answer":"OKX offers portfolio margin mode allowing cross-collateral efficiency for arbitrage positions. Phemex supports cross-margin but lacks OKX's portfolio-level margin optimization, requiring more capital allocation per position."}]}]
